    to generate a crop-specific schedule instantly.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Start With Your Last Frost Date</h2>

  <p>
    Your <strong>average last frost date</strong> is the typical final spring freeze in your area.
    It is based on historical probability, not certainty.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Some years frost ends earlier.</li>
    <li>Some years frost lingers.</li>
    <li>Elevation and exposure can shift local timing.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If you don’t know your frost date, see
    <a href="/guides/how-to-find-your-last-frost-date/">How to Find Your Last Frost Date</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Basic Formula</h2>

  <p><strong>Indoor start date = last frost date − recommended indoor weeks</strong></p>

  <p>
    Example:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Last frost: May 15</li>
    <li>Tomatoes: 6–8 weeks indoors</li>
    <li>Start window: March 20 – April 3</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The goal is to have seedlings ready for transplant — not oversized plants waiting indoors.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Warm-Season vs Cool-Season Crops</h2>

  <p>
    Not all crops respond the same way to early starts.
  </p>

  <h3>Warm-Season Crops</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Tomatoes</li>
    <li>Peppers</li>
    <li>Eggplant</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These require warm soil (around 60°F / 16°C or higher) at transplant.
    Starting too early rarely helps unless transplant timing changes.
  </p>

  <h3>Cool-Season Crops</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Broccoli</li>
    <li>Cabbage</li>
    <li>Lettuce</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These tolerate light frost and can often be transplanted before warm-season crops.
    Many are also suitable for direct sowing.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature Matters More Than Calendar Dates</h2>

  <p>
    Last frost is your anchor, but soil and air temperatures determine success.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Below 50°F (10°C): Warm-season crops stall.</li>
    <li>Below 40°F (4°C): Cold stress becomes likely.</li>
    <li>32°F (0°C): Frost damage possible.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If transplant timing does not shift, starting seeds earlier only extends indoor time — it does not extend the growing season.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Starting Too Early Backfires</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Leggy growth from light limitations</li>
    <li>Root-bound seedlings</li>
    <li>Higher risk of damping off</li>
    <li>Transplant shock from overgrown plants</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    For recovery strategies, see
    <a href="/guides/starting-seeds-too-early/">What Happens If You Start Seeds Too Early?</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Adjusting for Short Growing Seasons</h2>

  <p>
    In cold climates across northern U.S. states and comparable Canadian regions,
    the instinct is often to start everything earlier.
  </p>

  <p>
    In practice, better results usually come from:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Choosing earlier-maturing varieties</li>
    <li>Transplanting at proper soil temperatures</li>
    <li>Using light frost protection strategically</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Starting earlier only helps if it meaningfully advances transplant timing.
  </p>
</section>

